Skyrim Campaign Guide - For Adventure Creation
Campaign Overview & Setting
The World: An Alternate Skyrim
This campaign takes place in a parallel universe where the Dragonborn exists but has abandoned their destiny. Instead of answering the call to save the world, they've chosen a simple life as a fisherman, ignoring the growing threats across Skyrim. This creates a power vacuum where other heroes must step up to handle the crises that would normally fall to the Dragonborn.
Campaign Structure: Anthology Adventures
Episodic Format: Each session is a complete, self-contained adventure
Flexible Continuity: Players can bring the same characters or create new ones each session
Escalating Backdrop: While each adventure stands alone, the overarching threats grow more severe as the Dragonborn continues to ignore their duty
Heroic Opportunity: The players become the heroes Skyrim desperately needs

Adventure Creation Framework
Essential Adventure Components
1. The Core Structure Every adventure should follow this proven formula:
Hook Location: Always start in a tavern, inn, or safe gathering place
Quest Giver: A memorable NPC with a clear problem and compelling motivation
Journey: Travel to the adventure location with at least one encounter or complication
The Dungeon: Use the 5-Section structure (Guardian ΓåÆ Puzzle ΓåÆ Setback ΓåÆ Boss ΓåÆ Reward)
Resolution: Return to safety, collect rewards, gain 1 AP per player
2. Power Level Guidelines
Novice Adventures (0 AP): New heroes, local threats, basic rewards.
Apprentice Adventures (1-2 AP): Regional up-and-comers, organized threats, improved rewards.
Adept Adventures (3-4 AP): Well-known hold champions, significant threats, valuable rewards.
Expert Adventures (5-6 AP): Legendary heroes, province-wide threats, rare rewards.
Master Adventures (7+ AP): Mythic legends, world-ending dangers, epic rewards.
3. Encounter Loot Distribution This was identified as a gap in "The Pale Lady's Tomb" - loot should be pre-planned for smoother gameplay.
Pre-Guardian Encounters:
Minor Combat: 10-20 gold per player, 1 minor consumable (healing potion, etc.)
Social Success: Information, a useful contact, or a small favor owed
Section 1 (Guardian) Loot:
Combat Victory: 25-50 gold per player, 1-2 minor consumables
Hidden/Search Rewards: A piece of useful equipment or a clue to the main treasure
Section 2 (Puzzle) Loot:
Puzzle Success: A key item for the adventure, knowledge/lore, or a minor magical item
Bonus Discovery: Hidden compartment with gold or a consumable
Section 3 (Setback) Loot:
Overcoming the Setback: 30-60 gold per player, 1 useful consumable per 2 players
Creative Solutions: Bonus loot for thinking outside the box
Section 4 (Boss) Loot:
Boss Defeat: The session's major treasure (see Rewards Framework below)
Minion Cleanup: Minor additional gold and consumables
Section 5 (Final Treasure) Loot:
The Big Payoff: Primary quest reward, significant gold, and the adventure's signature magical item

